fields.title: You
fields.intro_description: Worried about privacy? You should. We are, too. That's why we don't store any personal information about you.

fields.title: Your Work
fields.intro_description:
Temporary contracts. Permanent job-hunt. Playing online poker for a living. Editing Wikipedia. Work can be many things. But economists still measure (un)employment the same way.


What’s work for you?

fields.title: Your Money
fields.intro_description:
The cash machine in your bank’s local branch fuels your life. But what if your source of money dries up? Doing small jobs here and there, selling stuff on ebay, asking family and friends for cash. That’s what young people do get by.
How do you make ends meet?

fields.title: Your Education
fields.intro_description:
Your teachers have always told you that being good at Maths and English, learning to type with ten fingers, enrolling auto mechanic training or studying law will guarantee you a quiet life.
What are the skills that you really need in your working life?

fields.title: Your Government
fields.intro_description:
What’s a minimum salary that doesn’t destroy jobs? How can we ensure that women make as much money as men? That’s what politicians debate. Some think we should pay everybody a universal income - with no obligation to work.
If you were Minister of Labour for one day, what would be your plan?

fields.title: Your Future
fields.intro_description:
A 38-hour week. A single-family, detached house. Retirement with 62. That might have been your parents’ work life plan. The circumstances have changed. Our generation is dreaming a different dream. But what’s still to come? Will self-driving cars bring our children to school?
How do you see your future World of Work?

fields.html_sentence: In France begging was considered a normal activity until the end of the 19th century. In the 20th century it went out of fashion and some beggars would even wear masks while doing their job.
As a young European chances are almost 50% that you owe money to your bank, family or friends. The median debt of young people in Europe is 5000 €.
Often theft in the workplace doesn't have anything to do with "real world" crime. Those who steal most are also those who work most. They think they're not paid enough.
Academics agree on this matter: social background and parents' opinions matter most when young people decide what to do with their lives.
The average McDonald's worker has to work 7 months to get what the company's CEO takes home in just 1 hour.

Studies in the sun

Spain is Erasmus destination #1. Granada in Andalusia is the capital of the study abroad programme. More than 2000 students come here every year. Erasmus is run by the EU but students also rely on their government’s willingness to co-sponsor their trip.
In Germany people seem to love their jobs. After a 10 million € win only every third man would quit his job. Women are even more attached to their work: only every fourth would pack it all in.
Distorted perception: The French are amongst those who are the most insecure about their jobs in Europe. At the same time their jobs are also the most stable.
If a government wants to increase birth rates, it’s more effective to build day nurseries and kindergartens, than to pay people for staying at home with their children. Seems to work even in Germany!
9 out of 10 French find it normal to “arrange” their CV and only 1 employer out of 5 actually check what people send them.

A continent of old people?

The old-age dependency ratio measures the number of elderly people as a share of those of working age. Places where old people rely on a small number of working young people are dark red.
Family disputes in sight: 9 out of 10 family business owners could not imagine selling their company.
Only 1 in 6 in Europe would start a business if they inherited money. Every third would buy a house.

The invasion of the robots?

Scientists at the University of Oxford have created a model to estimate which jobs will have been replaced by machines or robots 20 years from now. The bigger the bubbles in this chart the more a job is future-proof. Seems that clergy have made a good job choice. Bad luck for referees though.
professionally useful there.

Economists say that crises make people increase their efforts at work. But that does not seem to be the case for everybody. Three-quarters of Dutch workers do not see the financial crisis as a reason to work harder.

The gender pay gap - everybody talks about it but nobody actually sees it. That’s also what Finnish study shows: Female employees often consider themselves as well-paid as their male counterparts even if they aren’t.
1 out of 2 Europeans would be angry to learn that their boss monitors their professional emails. They don’t seem to realise that this can actually be legal.
Disappointed by your paycheck? In Portugal the minimum salary is only 566 €.
Taking care of your grand-parents can be a full time job. And therefore half of the European population thinks you should be paid for it by your government!
Nobody actually evaluates if career advice services are effective. We only know for sure that many counselors doubt that they’re doing a good job.
Every third immigrant has a university degree. That's much more than the general population.
Sheltered employment is a trap. Many policies see it as a springboard into the “regular” labor market. But only very few people manage to make the transition. In Austria it’s less than every 30th.
Young people are not interested in trade unions. Less than every 10th has a membership card.
You can tweak your CV as much as you want. If you have the wrong name or live in the wrong place you still get discriminated against. That’s why some governments try out anonymous CVs.

Older people are generally against a universal basic income. For young people it’s less of a problem to receive money without having to work for it. Economists say that financial incentives make us work harder but not necessarily smarter. It’s hard to say what the actual effects of a basic income on the labor market would be.
In France one out of ten students enrolls preparation classes for university, so called prépas, after they finish school. Some of them are 2 years long and extremely demanding.
Young people have the highest risk to be working but poor in Scandinavia. By the way, in most countries working women are less likely to need assistance from their relatives or the government.
In some countries, like Denmark, sperm donations are tax free.

If you’ve managed to leave your parents’ house consider yourself lucky. For young Europeans between 18 and 34 chances are almost 50 % that they still live with their parents. Half of them say it’s for financial reasons.
In Berlin, one third of the student population could imagine financing their studies with prostitution.

In Dresden, Germany, you can make 100 € by queuing for a night. Couples, who want to fix a wedding date at the local register office, are willing to pay that price. The office opens it’s schedule only twice a year and at 8 in the morning.
Sharing is caring? Yes, but sharing is also just a means to squeeze more value out your budget. According to Airbnb, many users couldn’t afford their home without renting it out on the platform.
Reading all articles on Wikipedia would take 7 years. And all this has been created by volunteers.

87% of Italians believe that young people now are less likely than their parents to find a job they actually like. But they look on the bright side: 50% say that they will at least be able to spend more time with their "famiglia"!

Neurosurgeons, soldiers, and art teachers are amongst those who consider their jobs as important for society. Securities traders, fashion designers, and gas station attendants think their jobs are not very meaningful.
Workers between 16 to 34 tend to be more satisfied with their jobs than their older colleagues. But they're also the first to leave when something annoys them.

Every sector has its drug taste! People working in construction consume cocaine and mushrooms, the gastronomic sector likes all sorts of substances. Amongst civil servants though there's not much interest in drugs.

How Europeans search for jobs.

Europeans search for jobs in unconventional ways. Only 6% use classified ads in Spain. In Austria 52% try their luck with unsolicited applications. Generally, the more opaque a job market, the more people rely on their personal networks in order to find work.

Early bird or late riser? Scientists have found out that that's part of your DNA. The difference between your natural rhythm and your social obligations is called "social jetlag". People who get up one hour too early, consume more cigarettes, alcohol, and coffee and have a one third higher risk of being obese.
Leaving it all behind? Not really! Since the economic crisis less people are willing to move to another European country for work.

The French don’t “friend” their bosses. Only 8 % are connected with their boss on Facebook. In Italy 33% are friends with their superiours. In the end, it’s a matter of individual judgement. No study has shown that befriending your boss on Facebook will boost your career.
Jobless = unhappy? Not necessarily! In Germany there’s a group of “happily jobless” who call themselves “Glückliche Arbeitslose”, in France, they go under the name of “Bomeurs”.
59%  did not receive any financial compensation during their last internship. 10% consider that they haven’t learned anything professionally useful there.
Two English students have made over £30,000 by renting out their faces for ads. They charge £100 per day.
Living far from work makes people unhappy. Psychologists have shown that commutes are the unhappiest moments of the day. The only thing with a similar sadness level is household work.

In 2010 75000 people went wwoofing, meaning they volunteered on an organic farm. And numbers are growing! But the concept is not entirely new. In so called Kibbutzim in Israel people have been working in exchange for food and shelter since the 1920s.
Pilot, veterinary, astronaut, writer... At least 7 out of 10 people do not work in their childhood dreamjobs.

A good idea to start saving now?

Today the interest rate of normal savings accounts gets eaten up by inflation. If you start saving 400 € a month now, you might be able to afford a house in 30 years. Not enough to motivate the majority of young people in Europe to save up.
In a recent case of "bossnapping" French media managers have been "detained" by their employees for more than 18 hours.

fields.source_title: Eurostat, Vice, Les inrocks, Glückliche Arbeitslose
